01:53.960 --> 01:55.519
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

01:56.960 --> 02:00.317
All right, Billy. Enough is enough.
Two days locked up in your room

02:00.520 --> 02:04.150
because Molly
broke up with you
is plenty.

02:04.400 --> 02:07.120
But I can't go back.
I can't face the kids.

02:07.320 --> 02:09.515
What do you plan to do
with your life?

02:09.720 --> 02:12.394
I don't know.
Join the circus
and become a clown.

02:12.600 --> 02:14.239
And all because of some little girl?

02:14.440 --> 02:17.672
She's not some little girl.
We were going steady.

02:17.880 --> 02:19.837
Then she left me for a junior.

02:20.040 --> 02:23.397
Well, why don't you fight for her?
Win her back.

02:23.600 --> 02:26.240
Dad, come on.
I can't compete.

02:26.440 --> 02:29.000
He's 6'1" and drives a convertible.

02:29.200 --> 02:31.760
I'm a midget with a Schwinn.

02:33.320 --> 02:36.074
Well, what is she,
the only girl in the world?

02:36.280 --> 02:38.556
Billy, do you know
how many girls
there are out there?

02:38.760 --> 02:40.274
They're all over the place.

02:40.480 --> 02:43.279
Thousands, millions of them,

02:43.960 --> 02:50.309
Beautiful, wonderful,
glorious, volup...
Lots of girls.

02:52.560 --> 02:54.517
Yeah, but I want Molly.

02:54.720 --> 02:57.360
That's only because
you can't have Molly.

02:58.400 --> 03:00.631
Billy, let me tell you a story.

03:00.840 --> 03:04.550
During the war,
this guy Herbie and I
became friends.

03:04.760 --> 03:08.993
Well, Herbie fell in love
with a wonderful
Italian girl, Carla.

03:09.200 --> 03:12.557
Thinking of Carla
was what got him
through the war.

03:12.760 --> 03:15.912
Well, Carla died,
and Herbie
nearly fell apart.

03:16.120 --> 03:18.032
He stayed in, drank.

03:18.240 --> 03:20.118
I've never seen anyone
so miserable.

03:20.320 --> 03:23.279
And then one day
Herbie came to me
and he said:

03:23.480 --> 03:26.473
"Chet, life must go on."

03:26.680 --> 03:28.831
And Herbie went on.

03:29.040 --> 03:31.874
A few years later,
he fell in love
with another woman,

03:32.080 --> 03:35.039
married her, and
they went to Jamaica
on their honeymoon,

03:35.240 --> 03:38.631
and she ran off with
a steel band.

03:39.480 --> 03:41.631
But Herbie went on.

03:41.840 --> 03:44.719
He married again,
and this time,
at the wedding reception,

03:44.920 --> 03:48.197
his bride left him
for the caterer.

03:49.240 --> 03:52.790
But still, Herbie went on.

03:53.080 --> 03:55.549
His next wife
ran off with his partner,

03:55.760 --> 04:00.596
who ran off with his business.
But still, Herbie went on.

04:00.800 --> 04:02.359
Because you see, Billy,

04:02.560 --> 04:04.916
he knew that there's
a whole world out there.

04:05.120 --> 04:07.954
He knew that somewhere,
around some corner,

04:08.160 --> 04:10.117
he would find happiness.

04:11.120 --> 04:13.237
Wow. I feel like a jerk.

04:13.440 --> 04:16.113
I mean, look at Herbie,
a lifetime of disasters.

04:16.320 --> 04:20.599
I had a week with
a 13-year-old shrimp who lisps

04:20.800 --> 04:22.439
and I'm gonna throw my life away?

04:22.640 --> 04:23.640
Thanks, Dad.

04:23.800 --> 04:25.757
Good boy.
I'll see you at breakfast.

04:25.960 --> 04:28.156
Hey, Dad, where's Herbie now?

04:28.360 --> 04:32.274
Oh, he's, uh,
in a mental institution.

04:34.360 --> 04:35.476
What?

04:35.680 --> 04:37.831
Yes. He just sits in a corner,

04:38.040 --> 04:41.431
talks in numbers
and makes lovely baskets.

04:41.640 --> 04:43.757
But...

04:43.960 --> 04:45.076
I thought...

04:45.280 --> 04:47.431
Well, I thought he always goes on?

04:47.640 --> 04:52.431
Well, Billy, please.
There's just so much
going on that a man can do.

04:52.680 --> 04:54.637
[♪♪♪]

05:02.600 --> 05:06.833
Are you going to tell Mr. Tate
that Corinne is moving in with Peter?

05:07.040 --> 05:08.040
Because if you are,

05:08.200 --> 05:10.795
that's two places
I won't have to set no more.

05:11.000 --> 05:14.038
No, Benson,
only one place, Corinne's.

05:14.240 --> 05:18.120
Two. Because when
Mr. Tate finds out,
it's gonna kill him.

05:18.320 --> 05:19.993
Good morning.
Good morning.

05:20.200 --> 05:22.192
JESSICA:
Good morning, Chester.

05:26.920 --> 05:27.920
Benson.

05:29.720 --> 05:31.552
I asked for
a three-minute egg.

05:31.760 --> 05:33.353
That is a
three-minute egg.

05:33.560 --> 05:34.835
This egg is raw.

05:35.040 --> 05:38.192
Well, what did you expect
when you ask for an egg
in three minutes?

05:38.400 --> 05:41.120
I got to get it out
of the refrigerator,

05:43.400 --> 05:46.313
get it onto a plate,
get it all the way in here.

05:46.520 --> 05:50.912
You want it cooked,
then you gotta give me
10 minutes.

05:55.360 --> 05:57.955
I have an announcement to make.

05:58.400 --> 05:59.516
Uh...

05:59.720 --> 06:02.280
Corinne is not here.

06:03.000 --> 06:05.435
I think that
we can see that,
Jessica.

06:05.640 --> 06:09.190
Well, yes, of course
you can, Chester,
because her seat is empty.

06:09.400 --> 06:11.596
Where is she?
Corinne

06:11.800 --> 06:14.440
is moving.
Moving? Where?

06:14.640 --> 06:16.518
Where? Where
is she moving?

06:16.720 --> 06:21.192
Oh, Chester, that is
a good question. Corinne is
moving into an apartment

06:21.400 --> 06:23.153
that she's gonna share
with someone.

06:23.360 --> 06:27.673
Oh, well, I'm not surprised.
Not yet.

06:28.480 --> 06:31.040
I'm sure she's at an age
when she wants to be on her own.

06:31.240 --> 06:33.152
And she's going to have
a roommate?
Yes, dear.

06:33.360 --> 06:36.034
Good. I really don't want her
living alone.

06:36.240 --> 06:37.560
Do we know the girl's family?

06:37.760 --> 06:40.639
Yes, yes, we do. We know
the family really quite well.

06:40.840 --> 06:43.355
As a matter of fact,
we're almost related.

06:43.560 --> 06:45.153
Good. Good. Who is it?

06:45.360 --> 06:48.353
Billy, run upstairs
and get Mother something.

06:48.560 --> 06:50.756
Why can't anybody ever talk
in front of me?

06:50.960 --> 06:53.839
I mean, I walk into a room
and conversation stops.

06:54.040 --> 06:55.315
I went around for years

06:55.520 --> 06:57.989
thinking a surprise party
was being planned for me.

07:00.680 --> 07:03.115
Well, I'm not leaving, Mom.
I'm not missing this.

07:03.320 --> 07:05.039
Jessica, who is the girl?

07:05.240 --> 07:07.152
What girl, Chester?

07:07.360 --> 07:09.875
The girl Corinne will be living with.

07:10.080 --> 07:15.712
The girl? Oh, the girl.
Oh, look, here's Corinne.

07:15.920 --> 07:18.230
I told Daddy
that you were moving, dear.

07:18.440 --> 07:20.671
Who is she moving in with?

07:20.880 --> 07:23.236
And Daddy thinks that's nice.
Isn't that nice, dear?

07:23.440 --> 07:24.669
Things are so much nicer

07:24.880 --> 07:27.998
when people think they're nice.
Don't you think so? I think so.

07:28.600 --> 07:30.831
You didn't tell him
who I was moving in with?

07:31.040 --> 07:32.394
No.

07:32.600 --> 07:34.114
I'm moving in with Peter.

07:34.320 --> 07:38.360
<i>Peter, Peter, pumpkin</i>
<i>eater, had a wife</i>
<i>and couldn't keep her</i>

07:39.360 --> 07:40.794
<i>Put her in a pumpkin shell,</i>

07:41.000 --> 07:42.841
[BOTH CHANTING]
<i>and there he kept her very well</i>

07:42.920 --> 07:44.593
Oh. I love that one.
Don't you, Daddy?

07:44.800 --> 07:45.916
[JESSICA GIGGLING]

07:47.800 --> 07:49.553
Corinne, what are you saying?

07:49.760 --> 07:50.760
Say...

07:50.920 --> 07:52.877
[SINGING "SAY IT ISN'T SO"]

07:58.360 --> 08:00.158
All right, stop!

08:00.400 --> 08:02.357
[SINGING "STOP!
IN THE NAME OF LOVE"]

08:03.880 --> 08:05.109
Shut up, Benson.

08:05.360 --> 08:06.760
[CONTINUES SINGING]

08:09.320 --> 08:11.391
All right, Corinne, one more time.

08:11.600 --> 08:13.557
[SINGING "SAY IT ISN'T SO"]

08:18.240 --> 08:20.880
I said, I'm moving in with Peter.

08:21.080 --> 08:22.878
Peter. Who's Peter?

08:23.640 --> 08:25.393
Peter Campbell, the tennis pro.

08:28.200 --> 08:31.079
That's it?
That's the big thing?

08:31.280 --> 08:33.590
I thought it would be
something good.

08:35.480 --> 08:39.360
Um... I'm sorry, Daddy.

08:40.320 --> 08:41.833
Goodbye.

08:44.400 --> 08:47.359
Goodbye, Major.
Yeah, all right.

08:48.240 --> 08:50.436
Goodbye, Benson.

08:50.640 --> 08:54.270
Corinne, if you need
anything, you call me,
okay?

08:54.480 --> 08:55.960
Yeah.

08:56.680 --> 09:00.230
But don't bring
your laundry around here,
because I ain't gonna do it.

09:02.480 --> 09:04.437
That's it?
You're just going to sit there

09:04.640 --> 09:07.155
while our daughter
throws her life away?

09:07.360 --> 09:09.431
Well, Chester,
I don't know what else to do.

09:09.640 --> 09:11.518
Get her back.
How?

09:11.720 --> 09:13.916
Well, you'd better
think of something,
Jessica

09:14.120 --> 09:16.476
because my blood pressure's
already red-lined it.

09:16.680 --> 09:20.560
All I have to do is stand up,
and I will have a cerebral
haemorrhage on the spot.

09:20.760 --> 09:23.150
Simon says, "Stand up."

09:23.760 --> 09:25.558
[♪♪♪]

09:27.760 --> 09:29.114
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

09:29.440 --> 09:30.920
What's going on, Corinne?

09:31.120 --> 09:33.191
Nothing.
Nothing? You're
upstairs packing,

09:33.400 --> 09:36.154
Mother's downstairs
crying, and
nothing's going on?

09:36.360 --> 09:39.910
I don't want to talk about it.
You know, it's funny, Corinne.

09:40.120 --> 09:43.033
All these years I couldn't
wait for one of us
to move out of the house

09:43.240 --> 09:45.516
and now you are

09:46.360 --> 09:47.680
and I'm kind of sad.

09:47.880 --> 09:50.952
It's better this way.
Well, tell me, Corinne.

09:51.160 --> 09:53.356
I can't.
Are you in love?

09:53.560 --> 09:56.234
Eunice, I can't talk about it.
You wouldn't understand.

09:56.440 --> 09:58.477
I would understand.

09:58.680 --> 09:59.875
I'm in love.

10:00.400 --> 10:02.551
You're in love?

10:03.000 --> 10:05.117
But you never go out.

10:05.840 --> 10:08.912
Who are you in love with,
United Parcel?

10:09.295 --> 10:11.456
Corinne, you're just gonna
have to take my word for it.

10:11.480 --> 10:14.075
I can't tell you who it is.
It's very complicated.

10:14.280 --> 10:17.318
Complicated, please,
you don't know from complicated.

10:17.520 --> 10:21.116
Believe me, if you knew
who was involved in
my situation, you'd faint.

10:21.320 --> 10:24.313
If you knew who
was involved in mine,
you'd drop dead.

10:25.080 --> 10:27.675
All right, Corinne.
All right.

10:27.880 --> 10:31.954
I happen to be in love
with a public figure.

10:32.160 --> 10:33.230
Peanuts.

10:33.440 --> 10:36.592
A married...
A married
public figure.

10:36.800 --> 10:38.075
Zip.

10:38.280 --> 10:40.033
All right, Corinne.

10:40.240 --> 10:42.118
I'm in love

10:42.320 --> 10:44.835
with Congressman
Walter McCallam.
Hmph.

10:45.040 --> 10:47.635
Top that.
I could.

10:47.840 --> 10:49.194
But I can't tell you.

10:49.400 --> 10:52.154
Well, I knew
you couldn't.
Mine's bigger.

10:53.240 --> 10:54.913
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

10:55.120 --> 10:57.077
A married congressman?
Right.

10:58.240 --> 10:59.833
How do you like this one?

11:00.040 --> 11:02.191
I'm moving in
with Peter Campbell

11:02.560 --> 11:04.279
[SCOFFS THEN CHUCKLES]

11:04.800 --> 11:07.235
who's also having
an affair with Mother.

11:07.440 --> 11:09.397
[LAUGHING]

11:10.560 --> 11:13.553
Corinne, you're
not allowed to lie.

11:14.640 --> 11:15.676
It's the truth.

11:21.560 --> 11:23.119
Mother?

11:23.720 --> 11:25.393
Our mother?

11:25.600 --> 11:27.831
The mother downstairs?

11:28.680 --> 11:30.319
Jessica?

11:30.520 --> 11:34.673
The redhead?
That's the one.

11:35.520 --> 11:37.079
You win.

11:38.120 --> 11:40.919
I can't believe it.

11:41.120 --> 11:42.998
I mean, it took me
20 years to believe

11:43.200 --> 11:45.635
she did it with Daddy.

11:48.480 --> 11:50.870
Oh, isn't this nice.

11:51.080 --> 11:52.480
Oh, I just love this.

11:52.680 --> 11:55.275
All the Tate women
are gathered here together.

11:55.480 --> 11:58.200
Well, you two probably
have a lot to talk about.

11:58.400 --> 11:59.400
Yes.
No.

11:59.560 --> 12:01.438
Uh, you two have
a lot not to talk about,

12:01.640 --> 12:03.950
in which case I'll still leave.

12:11.040 --> 12:12.599
Corinne.

12:18.080 --> 12:19.434
You know, Corinne,

12:19.640 --> 12:22.792
in life, people make mistakes.

12:23.000 --> 12:24.832
Little mistakes
and big mistakes.

12:25.040 --> 12:28.431
And I made a big mistake.

12:28.640 --> 12:33.237
Well, actually, I made
a huge mistake and
I am sorry. I...

12:33.440 --> 12:38.071
You have no idea
how terribly sorry I am.

12:38.280 --> 12:40.590
But you see,
I thought if I told you

12:40.800 --> 12:43.872
what a mistake I had made,
and how sorry I was,

12:44.080 --> 12:46.834
that it would make
everything all right.

12:48.520 --> 12:50.159
But, uh,

12:50.360 --> 12:53.512
now that I'm hearing it,
I realise that it's
just not enough.

12:53.720 --> 12:57.475
And I guess it probably
won't be enough

12:57.680 --> 13:00.718
for a long time to come.

13:02.520 --> 13:06.514
But I still want to say it.

13:08.880 --> 13:10.872
I am sorry.

13:14.360 --> 13:16.955
I'm a mother

13:17.160 --> 13:19.117
and I know you...

13:20.040 --> 13:23.192
You think I should have
known better.

13:23.960 --> 13:25.758
But Corinne,

13:27.120 --> 13:31.000
knowing better
doesn't always work out.

13:33.240 --> 13:35.391
So I'm sorry.

13:36.640 --> 13:37.835
But I guess I'm...

13:38.040 --> 13:41.317
I'm sorry about
a lot of things in my life.

13:42.080 --> 13:43.753
But most of all,

13:43.960 --> 13:46.919
I'm sorry for what's happened
between us.

13:49.480 --> 13:51.517
I'm going to miss you.

13:55.720 --> 13:57.677
[CRYING]

13:58.200 --> 14:00.271
Goodbye, Corinne.

14:00.480 --> 14:02.437
[♪♪♪]

14:06.560 --> 14:08.517
[♪♪♪]

14:09.600 --> 14:10.875
I've ruined my marriage

14:11.080 --> 14:13.720
I've ruined my life,
Corinne's left home

14:13.920 --> 14:16.560
and it's all because
I took tennis lessons.

14:16.760 --> 14:18.080
Okay, Jess.

14:18.280 --> 14:21.796
Let's just take one thing
at a time. What happened,
from the beginning?

14:22.400 --> 14:24.312
Well, it all started
two months ago

14:24.520 --> 14:26.273
when Chester gave me
a tennis racket.

14:26.480 --> 14:28.472
I don't know why
he gave me
a tennis racket.

14:28.680 --> 14:30.000
I never said I wanted one.

14:30.200 --> 14:32.317
I may have mentioned
I wanted a Cuisinart

14:32.520 --> 14:37.151
but I never once
mentioned that I wanted
a tennis racket.

14:37.360 --> 14:39.875
Oh, Mary, have you
got a Cuisinart?
They are wonderful.

14:40.080 --> 14:43.232
You can just throw your
knives away. You'll never
have to chop food again.

14:43.440 --> 14:44.715
What happened, Jess?

14:44.920 --> 14:47.355
When I first got mine,
all the food turned to mush...

14:47.560 --> 14:51.349
Jessica. What happened?

14:51.560 --> 14:54.951
Oh, well... Well,
Chester gave me
this tennis racket

14:55.160 --> 14:57.311
and I didn't want to appear
ungrateful, Mary.

14:57.520 --> 14:58.954
So I had to take tennis lessons.

14:59.160 --> 15:01.436
And because
I took tennis lessons,
I met Peter.

15:01.640 --> 15:02.756
And because I met Peter,

15:02.960 --> 15:03.916
[WHISPERING] I slept with him.

15:04.120 --> 15:05.349
Because I slept with him,

15:05.560 --> 15:07.392
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
now Chester's probably
gonna find out.

15:07.600 --> 15:10.434
And when Chester finds out,
my entire life is gonna be ruined.

15:10.640 --> 15:13.917
And it's all because
Chester gave me a tennis racket.

15:14.680 --> 15:17.752
This is actually Chester's fault.

15:18.760 --> 15:24.757
Mary? Mary, Mary,
have I got news.
I just got this cable at work.

15:24.960 --> 15:28.158
My son, Chuck,
is coming here
from Hawaii.

15:28.360 --> 15:31.239
Burt, this is signed
"Chuck and Bob."
Who's Bob?

15:31.440 --> 15:33.955
Oh, it's nobody.

15:34.160 --> 15:35.879
Well, he's obviously
somebody, Burt

15:36.080 --> 15:38.197
because he's coming
and he doesn't eat meat.

15:38.400 --> 15:40.710
Who doesn't eat meat?
Bob.

15:40.920 --> 15:44.231
Who's Bob?
I don't know.

15:45.120 --> 15:46.873
Somebody who's
coming with Chuck.

15:47.080 --> 15:49.879
Who's Chuck?
Burt's son. Who's Bob?

15:50.080 --> 15:53.437
I don't even know
who Chuck is.
Who's Bob?

15:53.640 --> 15:54.710
It's a dummy.

15:54.920 --> 15:58.914
Burt, I didn't ask you for his IQ,
I asked you who he was.

15:59.120 --> 16:00.156
A dummy.

16:00.360 --> 16:02.591
Well, your son Peter's
no genius, either.

16:02.800 --> 16:05.235
Where's Peter?
He's a dummy.

16:05.440 --> 16:07.671
But he's sweet, Burt.

16:07.880 --> 16:13.558
No, no, no, Bob.
Bob's a dummy. You know,
a little wooden doll.

16:13.760 --> 16:14.910
A wooden doll?

16:15.120 --> 16:18.511
Let me get this straight.
Your son, Chuck,
is coming here from Hawaii

16:18.720 --> 16:21.315
with Bob,
his little wooden doll.

16:22.400 --> 16:23.436
Right.

16:23.640 --> 16:27.759
And you thought I had
problems?
Come on, come on.

16:27.960 --> 16:30.077
I got him Bob
when he was a little kid.

16:30.280 --> 16:32.033
Bob?
Bob, yeah.

16:32.240 --> 16:34.160
Well, yeah, see, we don't
refer to him as a dummy

16:34.320 --> 16:36.232
because it kind of upsets Chuck.

16:36.440 --> 16:39.353
Not to mention driving Bob
completely crazy.

16:39.560 --> 16:42.234
No, now, he's had Bob all his life.
He took him everywhere.

16:42.440 --> 16:44.557
He took him to school, to camp,
into the Army...

16:44.760 --> 16:46.513
He took a doll into the Army?

16:46.720 --> 16:49.440
At least he could get into
the Army.

16:49.640 --> 16:52.155
Special services, Vietnam.
They entertained the troops.

16:52.360 --> 16:54.033
I'm sure they did.

16:54.240 --> 16:56.277
Hey, hey, hey.
He won a medal.

16:56.480 --> 16:58.153
Who? Chuck or Bob?

17:00.720 --> 17:02.200
Chuck.

17:04.359 --> 17:05.839
Mary, I have to go now.

17:06.040 --> 17:10.193
I have to go and see
what new disaster's
befallen me.

17:10.400 --> 17:11.550
Well, goodbye, Burt.

17:11.760 --> 17:16.630
I am so happy that
two more of your sons
are coming.

17:17.440 --> 17:19.511
One son.
The other's a dummy.

17:19.720 --> 17:22.234
Well, smart or dumb,
they're your children

17:22.440 --> 17:24.238
and you love them.

17:24.440 --> 17:26.396
[♪♪♪]

17:29.120 --> 17:31.077
[SPEAKING IN LATIN]

17:36.520 --> 17:38.034
Tim?

17:38.680 --> 17:40.637
[CONTINUES SPEAKING
IN LATIN]

17:42.320 --> 17:46.758
I had to come, Tim.
I had to see you
one last time.

17:47.360 --> 17:50.512
I moved in with that man
I told you about.

17:52.960 --> 17:56.510
But I had to see you
once more and
tell you how I feel.

17:56.720 --> 17:58.791
I love you, Tim.

17:59.000 --> 18:00.480
I know it's crazy to want you.

18:00.680 --> 18:02.717
I mean, people would say,
"Why him? Why Tim?

18:02.920 --> 18:04.354
He's not that terrific-looking."

18:08.760 --> 18:11.878
I mean, you're cute,
Tim, but face it,
you're no Al Pacino.

18:12.080 --> 18:14.595
And who knows what
your body is like
under that outfit.

18:14.800 --> 18:18.191
Look at you, you go around
wearing a little black dress.

18:18.400 --> 18:19.914
But I still want you.

18:20.640 --> 18:22.996
Tim, please?

18:23.200 --> 18:26.591
I'll leave him.
Come with me.

18:26.800 --> 18:28.314
I know you want to.

18:28.520 --> 18:31.399
If you left,
God would understand.

18:32.920 --> 18:34.912
He's seen a lot.
He's millions of years old.

18:35.120 --> 18:38.397
What do you think there is
that he hasn't seen?

18:38.880 --> 18:40.553
No, huh?

18:41.680 --> 18:43.751
Tim, could you stop
praying for just a minute?

18:43.960 --> 18:46.634
It's making me kind of crazy.

18:47.040 --> 18:49.600
Okay, fine.

18:49.800 --> 18:51.678
It doesn't matter,
you won't drown me out.

18:51.880 --> 18:54.793
You're gonna hear this
before I leave forever.

18:55.440 --> 18:59.639
I will stay with this man, Tim,
but I will always think of you.

18:59.840 --> 19:03.436
When he takes me in his arms,
I'll pretend it's you.

19:05.000 --> 19:09.677
And when he
whispers my name,
I'll pretend it's you.

19:10.680 --> 19:14.879
And when I'm with him,
I'll pretend it's you.

19:15.680 --> 19:17.319
So that's it, Tim.

19:17.520 --> 19:21.355
All the praying
in the world will not
stop me from loving you.

19:23.200 --> 19:24.919
Goodbye, Tim.

19:26.000 --> 19:27.832
I love you.

19:38.360 --> 19:41.956
Father Tim?
Father Tim.

19:42.160 --> 19:44.152
Take it easy.

19:45.560 --> 19:47.119
God is not deaf.

19:49.480 --> 19:51.437
[♪♪♪]

19:55.800 --> 19:56.870
Godfather?

19:57.080 --> 20:00.437
GODFATHER:
Over here, Danny.
Over here.

20:01.400 --> 20:04.518
Godfather?
Ah. Here I am, Danny.

20:04.720 --> 20:07.030
Danny, I'm in the middle
of a catastrophe.

20:07.240 --> 20:11.757
This is my only
healthy tomato plant.

20:11.960 --> 20:12.960
Look.

20:13.120 --> 20:15.077
[MUTTERING]

20:15.880 --> 20:17.633
You know what this is here?
Uh-uh.

20:17.840 --> 20:19.240
Tomato bugs.

20:19.440 --> 20:22.035
These bugs live
for only one thing in life:

20:22.240 --> 20:23.754
Destroying tomato plants.

20:23.960 --> 20:25.440
Hey, nice work, huh?

20:25.640 --> 20:27.632
Aye. What I want to know
is this:

20:27.840 --> 20:29.399
In the middle of the
largest city in the world,

20:29.600 --> 20:33.753
where there is no agriculture
to speak of, on the roof of
a 20-storey building,

20:33.960 --> 20:36.520
how they know
there's tomatoes here,
huh?

20:37.400 --> 20:38.550
I don't know.
Eh.

20:38.760 --> 20:41.639
Hey, maybe there was
a couple of bugs on a farm
somewhere in the Midwest,

20:41.840 --> 20:43.513
and one bug said
to the other bug:

20:43.720 --> 20:45.791
"Hey, let's go see
what's doing
in Manhattan, huh?"

20:46.000 --> 20:47.957
[LAUGHING]

20:49.600 --> 20:51.876
That's not funny, Danny.

20:52.080 --> 20:54.117
These tomatoes are dying.

20:54.320 --> 20:58.280
These tomato plants are dying
and I can't save them.

20:58.960 --> 21:02.237
Oh, Danny, I've been reading
the obituaries the last few days

21:02.440 --> 21:05.831
and I look, and I look,
and never do I see
the name of Burt Campbell.

21:06.040 --> 21:09.431
And I ask myself,
"Hey, why don't I see
this name?"

21:10.080 --> 21:11.275
Well, uh,

21:11.480 --> 21:13.517
it's because he's not dead yet.

21:13.720 --> 21:17.714
Ah. Well, that certainly
clears up the mystery, eh?

21:17.920 --> 21:21.231
I was thinking that probably was it.
Yeah, that was it.

21:21.440 --> 21:24.911
What are you waiting for,
Danny, huh? He should die
of old age?

21:25.120 --> 21:27.635
Godfather, I just don't know
how to do it.

21:27.840 --> 21:29.718
You don't have
to be an engineer, Danny.

21:29.920 --> 21:32.754
You take the gun. You point it.
You pull the trigger.

21:32.960 --> 21:35.600
Be nice if he was in the room.

21:36.160 --> 21:40.154
So, Danny, you be
a nice boy, huh? You
go home and kill Burt.

21:40.360 --> 21:45.355
Godfather, I just can't do it.
Look, I know you said
in order for me to leave

21:45.560 --> 21:47.119
I had to do you a favour.
Yeah.

21:47.320 --> 21:49.676
Okay, but couldn't you give me
something else to do?

21:49.880 --> 21:52.839
Oh, my. What did you
have in mind, Danny?
You wanna clean out my garage?

21:53.040 --> 21:56.397
You wanna simonise the limousine?
A deal's a deal, Danny.

21:56.600 --> 21:58.273
Besides, it's out of my hands now.

21:58.480 --> 22:01.234
I'm sorry. Mr. Lefkowitz
wants it done.

22:01.440 --> 22:03.352
Well, couldn't I talk to Mr. Lefkowitz?

22:03.560 --> 22:05.631
No way. Please, Danny.

22:05.840 --> 22:07.433
Lefkowitz talks to nobody, nobody.

22:07.640 --> 22:10.633
Mr. Lefkowitz doesn't even talk
to Mrs. Lefkowitz.

22:10.840 --> 22:13.720
First of all, you can't
pry him away from his
cockamamie stamp collecti...

22:13.880 --> 22:15.633
Godfather,
I can't do it.
I just can't do it.

22:15.840 --> 22:19.197
All right, Danny.
You listen to me now, eh?

22:19.400 --> 22:22.359
Come over here.
This is your last chance.

22:22.560 --> 22:24.279
You take this key.

22:24.480 --> 22:26.597
This is a key to a
remote cabin in the woods

22:26.800 --> 22:29.395
where, in the next two days,
you will kill Burt.

22:29.600 --> 22:31.831
You invite him to go fishing
with you...
Fishing?

22:32.040 --> 22:33.952
Well, if you tell him
the real reason

22:34.160 --> 22:36.595
I don't think
he's gonna wanna go, eh?

22:37.160 --> 22:40.312
All right. In the cabin,
there's a fireplace.

22:40.520 --> 22:42.955
In the chimney
of the fireplace,
there's a gun.

22:43.160 --> 22:45.800
The body,
you just leave there,
and we'll take care of it.

22:46.000 --> 22:48.196
Danny? Wait.

22:48.400 --> 22:51.518
You're such a
handsome boy,
nice-looking, you know.

22:51.720 --> 22:53.677
I don't want to see
your body in Brooklyn,

22:53.880 --> 22:56.952
your face in the Bronx.
That would upset me.

22:57.160 --> 23:00.471
Godfather, I just can't do it.

23:05.000 --> 23:09.791
GODFATHER:
You just destroyed
my only healthy tomato plant.

23:10.240 --> 23:13.517
And you seriously injured
my doorman.

23:14.880 --> 23:16.075
I think you can kill Burt.

23:16.280 --> 23:18.237
[♪♪♪]

23:21.640 --> 23:22.640
[♪♪♪]

